The Objective-C possibilities are:

    &quot;...&quot;

A C-style string of type `char *`, supports Unicode, current Clang compiler stores as UTF-8 YMMV.

    @&quot;...&quot;

An Objective-C string of type `NSString *`, supports Unicode

    &#39;...&#39;

A character literal, can contain 1-4 characters (GNU/Clang compilers as int is 32-bits, YMMV) and the type is `int` (NOT `char`). Current Clang compiler issues warnings for 2, 3 &amp; &gt; 4 character literals –&#160;the latter is truncated on the *left* to fit 32-bits. Variations exist for wide (`L&#39;.&#39;`) and Unicode (`u&#39;.&#39;` &amp; `U&#39;.&#39;`), read the C spec or good book for these.

There is more, e.g. adjacent literal strings are concatenated, again read the C spec or a good book and then figure out how it works for Objective-C strings (not sure its documented anywhere but its logical...)

Why YMMV? It&#39;s C (plenty of defined uncertainty) and Objective-C (simply ill-defined), enough said.

No links, further research left as an exercise ;-)

